Check variable types: nominal, ordinal, discrete or continious¶

In [10]:
# A method I created in another data analytics project
for col in df.columns:
    if df[col].dtype == 'object':
        print(col + ': Nominal') # Check if an object (nominal)
    elif len(df[col].unique()) <= 10: # Check if ordinal
        print(col + ': Ordinal')
    elif df[col].dtype == 'int64':
        print(col + ': Discrete') # Check if discrete
    else:
        print(col + ': Continuous') # Check if continious

We can check 'Age', 'DailyRate', 'DistancFromHome', 'HourlyRate', 'NumCompaniesWorked', 'PercentSalaryHike', 'PerformanceRating', 'RelationshipSatisfication'.¶

We check for the center (mean/median), the spread using standard deviation and the range (min to max). The justifications is that the mean and median will give us a good idea of the center of the variable not including the outliers, while the standard deviation will tell us how it spreads while the range gives us the min and max which is important to know¶

Check if you need to create new attribute(s) or remove redundant attribute(s)¶

I remove the EmployeeCount and Over18 as they are not needed (redundant).¶

I create a new variable called MonthlyIncome based on the MonthlySalary variable and also turn the MonthlyIncome variable into a numerical data type since it is an object, from this we can also find the quartiles (this is a new feature also)¶

In [22]:
df = df.drop(['EmployeeCount', 'Over18'], axis=1)
In [23]:
df['MonthlySalary'] = pd.to_numeric(df['MonthlyIncome'], errors='coerce') # It replaces any empty strings with NANs
df = df.drop(['MonthlyIncome'], axis=1) # Drop old and keep new
In [24]:
df['MonthlySalary'] = pd.to_numeric(df['MonthlySalary'], errors='coerce')
In [25]:
df['Salary_Quartile'] = pd.qcut(df['MonthlySalary'], q=4, labels=False)
df['Salary_Category'] = pd.cut(df['MonthlySalary'], bins=[0, 2500, 5000, 7500, 10000, np.inf], labels=['Low', 'Moderately Low', 'Moderate', 'High', 'Very High'])
